title.narrative: Output 2.4 Education system is capable to provide quality and inclusive learning and development to the most disadvantaged children and adolescents.

description.narrative: UNICEF supported the Ministry of Education and Science (MoES) to adopt a new inclusion policy and introduce monitoring mechanisms to ensure that no child is left behind. About 15,000 children started the new school year in 50 pilot schools, which are becoming more inclusive and responsive to their special education needs, with special attention given to children with disabilities and language minorities. With UNICEF support, 19,126 children were enrolled in Grade 1 in Bishkek through electronic school registry for the first time, which enabled equitable access to education regardless of their socio-economic background. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:27/01/2020

actual.value: 2020:Sector Strategy currently being finalsied with the support of UNICEF as Coordinating Agency of the GPE grant. UNICEF is playinga vital role in quality assurance and coordination of development partners' inputs

title.narrative: System Strengthening - Multilingual Ed. - Community engagement in multilingual / mother-tongue education - score (1-4), see guidance

baseline.value: Policy allows less than half of concerned children to learn in a language they understand

target.value: 2022:Policy allows the large majority of concerned children to learn in a language they understand. This is partially reflected in the curriculum and/or implementation plans

actual.value: 2020:Education Sector Plan currently under development. Whilst multi-lingual education is considered and promoted several times in the current draft, UNICEF is promoting imporved reference to mother-tongue based multi-lingual education.

title.narrative: System Strengthening - EMIS - National EMIS provides quality and timely data - score (1-4), see guidance

baseline.value: Score 1: Education data are of questionable reliability and are not all relevant. EMIS data are ready to be used less than one year after the end of the school year

target.value: 2022:Reliable and relevant education data are collected. EMIS data (or statistical yearbook) are ready to be used less than 3 months after the end of the school year

actual.value: 2020:Open EMIS modules currently being tested in pilot schools
